{
  "doc_id": "10304",
  "text": "Another assumed to play a role in development of STS is the amount of perceived social support. Social support is a broad, complex, and may have various forms [CITATION_1] . Relationship between perceived social support and STS has been established in several studies. Studies demonstrated that nurses and trauma workers who received high levels of social support found to have less STS symptoms [CITATION_2] . The qualitative literature also identified that ED nurses viewed social support as preventive and beneficial tool for the management of STS [CITATION_3] . It can be said that there is a consensus in the literature to recognize social support as a protective factor against developing of STS among ED nurses. Social support reduces the effect of work stress on the nurses who are exposed to stressful situations such as helping patients who scrimmage with death. Thus, reduce the occurrence of STS symptoms [CITATION_4] . However, it may be more helpful to determine which social supportive behaviors and which sources of support would help ED nurses more to protect them from STS.",
